WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.040
We have Sean Cross, who's going to be talking about Visualizing Data Analysis Pipelines

00:00:04.040 --> 00:00:07.000
with Pandas Tutor and Tidy Data Tutor.

00:00:07.000 --> 00:00:09.940
Good afternoon, everyone.

00:00:09.940 --> 00:00:16.559
So this is a real organic screenshot of my desktop by day and a similar screenshot by

00:00:16.559 --> 00:00:20.000
night.

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:23.760
You could easily say that code dominates my work life.

00:00:23.760 --> 00:00:25.639
And I believe that code is still important.

00:00:25.639 --> 00:00:28.559
I think that's part of the reason why we're here at posit.conf.

00:00:28.840 --> 00:00:33.959
We're not at tableau.conf, we're not at low-code, no-code.conf.

00:00:33.959 --> 00:00:40.080
Those things are certainly important and no negative judgment on my part, but I think

00:00:40.080 --> 00:00:45.680
that there's still a really important thing about building lasting visual infrastructure

00:00:45.680 --> 00:00:47.639
with code.

00:00:47.639 --> 00:00:52.320
But there are some issues with code that we just can't get around.

00:00:52.320 --> 00:00:54.240
Code can be intimidating.

00:00:54.240 --> 00:00:57.759
You hear about you're inheriting a new code base and you're like, oh my gosh, I can't

00:00:57.959 --> 00:00:59.480
believe I have to get into this.

00:00:59.480 --> 00:01:01.200
You get into that code and it can be opaque.

00:01:01.200 --> 00:01:04.400
You can read the code several times and you don't even really understand what's going

00:01:04.400 --> 00:01:06.959
on inside the code itself.

00:01:06.959 --> 00:01:07.959
And it can be overwhelming.

00:01:07.959 --> 00:01:12.360
You've got like a ton of code files that you need to integrate into a process that you're

00:01:12.360 --> 00:01:17.160
in charge of and it's just a lot to handle.

00:01:17.160 --> 00:01:25.239
And to me, this kind of sounds, these ideas of what can be wrong with code, it sounds

00:01:25.239 --> 00:01:29.480
like data in a lot of circumstances, right?

00:01:29.480 --> 00:01:34.400
What is different with this audience, though, is that most of us have a data science background.

00:01:34.400 --> 00:01:40.599
We've got all of this knowledge about tools that we can use to dig into data and to kind

00:01:40.599 --> 00:01:47.839
of overcome some of those challenges that I've discussed that data and code share.

00:01:47.839 --> 00:01:55.720
So a question that I really want you to ask yourself is, what could you build if you could

00:01:55.720 --> 00:02:01.440
apply your favorite data tools to your code?

00:02:01.440 --> 00:02:03.160
This is John McCarthy.

00:02:03.160 --> 00:02:08.440
He invented a lot of the fundamentals of computer science, including the programming language

00:02:08.440 --> 00:02:09.440
Lisp.

00:02:09.440 --> 00:02:12.679
And he also had this great idea that unfortunately I think has kind of been forgotten, which

00:02:12.679 --> 00:02:16.639
is this idea of code as data or code is data.

00:02:16.960 --> 00:02:22.199
And what I mean by this, this phrase code is data really refers to the idea that source

00:02:22.199 --> 00:02:27.320
code written in a programming language can be manipulated as data.

00:02:27.320 --> 00:02:30.520
And I don't know about you, but that sounds really exciting to me, right?

00:02:30.520 --> 00:02:36.759
Because we've got all these incredible data transformation and manipulation tools that

00:02:36.759 --> 00:02:37.839
we're all very familiar with.

00:02:37.839 --> 00:02:43.399
We've been learning about them for the last day at least, including yesterday and this

00:02:43.399 --> 00:02:44.399
weekend.

00:02:45.080 --> 00:02:49.360
Wouldn't it be great if we could apply some of these tools to code?

00:02:49.360 --> 00:02:53.919
And in R especially, this is kind of going on in the background in ways that we're not

00:02:53.919 --> 00:02:54.919
even aware of.

00:02:54.919 --> 00:02:59.559
So take, for example, the single line of code plot 1 to 10, right?

00:02:59.559 --> 00:03:01.440
Makes a very simple plot.

00:03:01.440 --> 00:03:06.160
But how does R know that the way that we're specifying the integers from 1 to 10 is with

00:03:06.160 --> 00:03:09.160
this expression 1 colon 10, right?

00:03:09.160 --> 00:03:12.960
There are lots of different ways you could write that in R. Yet R knows that that's what

00:03:12.960 --> 00:03:14.279
we wrote in the code.

00:03:14.279 --> 00:03:21.839
And then it actually puts it into the y-axis label here on this graph, which is kind of

00:03:21.839 --> 00:03:22.839
funny.

00:03:22.839 --> 00:03:28.160
So the two things I want to discuss for the rest of this talk is I want to show an example

00:03:28.160 --> 00:03:32.639
of what can be built with this idea of code as data.

00:03:32.639 --> 00:03:36.839
And then I want to point you on some directions of how you can build with this concept of

00:03:36.839 --> 00:03:39.160
code as data.

00:03:39.160 --> 00:03:43.839
So I work in the data science lab at the Fred Hutch Cancer Center in Seattle, Washington.

00:03:43.839 --> 00:03:50.000
And I am extremely privileged, because I get to work with these incredible biomedical data

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:53.679
science practitioners and these incredible health care providers.

00:03:53.679 --> 00:03:58.919
And what a lot of them do is that they spend half of their time in the lab at the bench,

00:03:58.919 --> 00:04:00.860
or they spend half their time in the clinic.

00:04:00.860 --> 00:04:04.600
And they spend the other half of their time kind of doing this, right?

00:04:04.600 --> 00:04:05.600
They're looking at their computer.

00:04:05.600 --> 00:04:07.759
And they're looking at data.

00:04:07.759 --> 00:04:09.460
They're transforming data.

00:04:09.460 --> 00:04:16.640
And a lot of the main data artifact that they're dealing with all the time is with data frames,

00:04:16.640 --> 00:04:19.359
data tables that we're familiar with.

00:04:19.359 --> 00:04:24.559
And the way that they choose to manipulate those data frames is through writing code.

00:04:24.559 --> 00:04:29.279
There's a lot of R written at Fred Hutch and a lot of Python written at Fred Hutch.

00:04:29.279 --> 00:04:34.920
And these are just kinds of the tools of the trade in biomedical data science.

00:04:34.920 --> 00:04:39.959
And an artifact within this code that I'm sure many of us are familiar with is the data

00:04:39.959 --> 00:04:41.640
analysis pipeline.

00:04:41.640 --> 00:04:45.320
So we want to break down one of these data analysis pipelines a little bit.

00:04:45.320 --> 00:04:47.000
The first speaker mentioned penguins.

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:49.440
I'm going to talk about penguins now.

00:04:49.440 --> 00:04:56.959
So the number one is pointing to this variable penguins, which represents and contains a

00:04:56.959 --> 00:05:02.959
data frame about measurements of penguins taken during a scientific study.

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:06.799
Number two is a pipe operator.

00:05:06.799 --> 00:05:14.440
And what the pipe operator does is that it takes what's on the left-hand side of the

00:05:14.440 --> 00:05:22.320
pipe operator, in this case, the data frame penguins, and it makes it the first argument

00:05:22.320 --> 00:05:28.079
to the function on the right-hand side of the pipe operator, which in this case is select.

00:05:28.079 --> 00:05:32.880
So what's happening here is that the select function is picking out these two individual

00:05:32.880 --> 00:05:38.399
columns from the penguins data set, the species of the penguin and the bill length in millimeters

00:05:38.399 --> 00:05:40.440
of the penguins.

00:05:40.440 --> 00:05:45.640
And what's nice about this kind of data analysis pipeline framework is that as long as the

00:05:45.640 --> 00:05:50.239
function on the right-hand side produces a data frame, you can chain together these functions.

00:05:50.239 --> 00:05:56.880
And it's kind of like a step-by-step recipe of the data manipulations that are happening

00:05:56.880 --> 00:05:58.239
to this data set.

00:05:58.239 --> 00:05:59.519
We're going to select these two columns.

00:05:59.519 --> 00:06:02.839
We're going to group the rows by the species of the penguin.

00:06:02.839 --> 00:06:06.519
We're going to arrange the rows in descending order according to bill length within each

00:06:06.519 --> 00:06:07.519
individual group.

00:06:07.519 --> 00:06:12.440
And then we're going to select the top row in each group is essentially what these five

00:06:12.440 --> 00:06:15.640
lines of code say.

00:06:15.640 --> 00:06:20.600
And I'm explaining these data analysis pipelines to people relatively often, either people

00:06:20.600 --> 00:06:25.079
who I'm onboarding them to some data analysis code because they're going to be changing

00:06:25.079 --> 00:06:27.839
it or they want to adapt it for their own purposes.

00:06:27.839 --> 00:06:33.200
Or I also do some teaching in different contexts at Fred Hutch.

00:06:33.200 --> 00:06:38.559
And so if I want to explain, for example, this filter function, I might draw a diagram

00:06:38.559 --> 00:06:45.079
like this and say, OK, on the left-hand side of the pipe, this is the status of the data

00:06:45.079 --> 00:06:46.079
frame.

00:06:46.079 --> 00:06:50.640
Then we're going to cross all of these rows out because they're going to get filtered

00:06:50.640 --> 00:06:51.640
out.

00:06:51.640 --> 00:06:53.799
And then the rows that are remaining move up to the top of the data frame.

00:06:53.799 --> 00:06:59.040
And it's the same kind of situation with the summarize example on the right-hand side.

00:06:59.040 --> 00:07:03.440
So after drawing enough of these diagrams, I thought, well, maybe I could automate this

00:07:03.440 --> 00:07:04.600
process a little bit.

00:07:04.600 --> 00:07:13.839
So I, along with colleagues of mine, Sam Lau and Philip Guo, built tidydatatutor.com and

00:07:13.839 --> 00:07:20.839
also similarly pandastutor.com, which automates the creation of these diagrams.

00:07:20.880 --> 00:07:25.959
So for example, if we start with the code that I was discussing before, the first thing

00:07:25.959 --> 00:07:31.420
that would get illustrated by Tidy Data Tutor is the select operation.

00:07:31.420 --> 00:07:34.720
So as you can see, we're picking out these two individual columns.

00:07:34.720 --> 00:07:38.720
The arrows show that the columns move from really what's going on the left-hand side

00:07:38.720 --> 00:07:42.559
of the pipe to the right-hand side of the pipe.

00:07:42.559 --> 00:07:45.079
Then we're going to group by the species.

00:07:45.079 --> 00:07:47.799
And so the species is highlighted on the left-hand side.

00:07:47.799 --> 00:07:54.519
And then the group that each row is in according to the species gets an individual color according

00:07:54.519 --> 00:07:58.559
to the group on the right-hand side.

00:07:58.559 --> 00:08:04.119
Then we're arranging within each group according to descending order.

00:08:04.119 --> 00:08:06.440
So the rows get rearranged.

00:08:06.440 --> 00:08:13.519
And the arrows show where each individual row moves in that arrangement operation.

00:08:13.519 --> 00:08:20.000
And then finally, we're taking the top row off of each group of the data frame

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:28.880
and just returning the maximum build length for each species in the final data frame.

00:08:28.880 --> 00:08:34.400
So this project has been pretty popular so far.

00:08:34.400 --> 00:08:37.280
Like I mentioned, there's also pandastutor.com.

00:08:37.280 --> 00:08:41.080
And a lot of these ideas from Tidy Data Tutor and from Pandastutor

00:08:41.080 --> 00:08:46.280
were inspired by our colleague, Philip Guo, who built pythontutor.com.

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:52.719
So those projects are just kind of like one example

00:08:52.719 --> 00:08:59.239
of what can be built with this idea of code as data.

00:08:59.239 --> 00:09:02.479
I now want to talk just a little bit and kind of point you

00:09:02.479 --> 00:09:08.239
all in the direction of how maybe you could start building things with this idea.

00:09:08.239 --> 00:09:11.400
And I really hope that this will facilitate a conversation

00:09:11.400 --> 00:09:16.919
and that we can talk after this session.

00:09:16.919 --> 00:09:22.679
The first thing I want to mention is a paper which actually describes

00:09:22.679 --> 00:09:29.919
how a couple packages work together that were built by myself, Lucy D'Agostino-McGowan,

00:09:29.919 --> 00:09:31.799
and Jeff Leak.

00:09:31.799 --> 00:09:37.359
That paper is called Tools for Analyzing R-Code the Tidy Way.

00:09:37.359 --> 00:09:43.039
Secondly, I really encourage everyone to read the metaprogramming sections.

00:09:43.039 --> 00:09:50.719
It's a couple chapters of Advanced R, which is available online for free.

00:09:50.719 --> 00:09:53.559
And the other thing that I encourage everyone

00:09:53.559 --> 00:09:58.719
to do in terms of an entree into what packages can help you treat your code

00:09:58.719 --> 00:10:03.039
as data is to mess around with the rlang package.

00:10:03.039 --> 00:10:05.159
It's a great package to explore.

00:10:05.159 --> 00:10:07.799
And when I really got into it, it really changed

00:10:07.799 --> 00:10:12.039
how I see both the code that I write and other R-Code

00:10:12.039 --> 00:10:15.919
that I have to approach through my work.

00:10:15.919 --> 00:10:17.280
Yeah, so that's really it.

00:10:17.280 --> 00:10:19.760
I really appreciate your attention, and thank you so much.

00:10:19.760 --> 00:10:20.260
Thank you.

00:10:26.400 --> 00:10:28.760
Thanks, John.

00:10:28.760 --> 00:10:30.840
So no questions in Slido right now, but are there

00:10:30.840 --> 00:10:33.280
any questions from the audience that you immediately had?

00:10:33.280 --> 00:10:34.679
Yeah, go ahead.

00:10:34.679 --> 00:10:36.239
Or actually, no, I'll run this to you.

00:10:42.359 --> 00:10:46.159
Hello, so you introduced this as a useful tool

00:10:46.159 --> 00:10:50.000
for new people who might be taking over the code base.

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:55.960
Has this been helpful in explaining what you do to non-data people?

00:10:55.960 --> 00:10:57.719
That's a great question.

00:10:57.719 --> 00:11:01.719
So the answer is absolutely yes.

00:11:01.719 --> 00:11:07.719
I've used it before in meetings, both with people

00:11:07.719 --> 00:11:10.119
who have a coding background and people who don't,

00:11:10.119 --> 00:11:13.799
really to just explain how certain decisions were

00:11:13.799 --> 00:11:15.440
made during a data analysis.

00:11:15.440 --> 00:11:19.239
And also to give them another artifact,

00:11:19.239 --> 00:11:22.679
both to verify that the logic that I'm

00:11:22.679 --> 00:11:25.640
using during a data analysis process

00:11:25.640 --> 00:11:28.919
is a logic that they agree with.

00:11:28.919 --> 00:11:32.359
And it also is an artifact that helps them really

00:11:32.359 --> 00:11:36.280
have something to point to and gives us something much deeper

00:11:36.280 --> 00:11:39.400
to discuss in terms of really the decisions that

00:11:39.400 --> 00:11:44.159
are made as we're doing an ongoing iterative data

00:11:44.159 --> 00:11:44.960
analysis together.

00:11:50.159 --> 00:11:51.359
Any other questions?

00:11:52.359 --> 00:12:00.200
I have a little addition on the code that I've made.

00:12:00.200 --> 00:12:04.880
So what I usually see when these things are being explained,

00:12:04.880 --> 00:12:08.359
like the pipe operator that's been used on multiple processes

00:12:08.359 --> 00:12:10.760
that are used on top of each other.

00:12:10.760 --> 00:12:14.919
And usually, these things are being explained with tables,

00:12:14.919 --> 00:12:18.239
just like to explain how a left join or a right join

00:12:18.239 --> 00:12:20.400
or an inner join or something works.

00:12:20.440 --> 00:12:23.280
And I think perhaps it even works better

00:12:23.280 --> 00:12:28.320
to explain that to non-data people when this being used

00:12:28.320 --> 00:12:33.119
in real visualizations, when you aggregate certain things

00:12:33.119 --> 00:12:37.080
or when you do these pipe operators on the several steps

00:12:37.080 --> 00:12:40.919
that are involved in the full stack of those five

00:12:40.919 --> 00:12:43.400
manipulations that you did on the raw data of the,

00:12:43.400 --> 00:12:46.239
I think the penguins data set or something.

00:12:46.239 --> 00:12:48.400
When a real scatterplot or something

00:12:48.400 --> 00:12:50.440
is being used on just the raw data,

00:12:50.440 --> 00:12:54.159
and then the grouping, and then the filtering,

00:12:54.159 --> 00:12:56.000
and the aggregation.

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:59.320
Because then you can really see from a non-data perspective

00:12:59.320 --> 00:13:04.599
person that you see what the unit of analysis

00:13:04.599 --> 00:13:06.280
is in your data later on when you

00:13:06.280 --> 00:13:11.039
do the aggregation versus what is the unit of observation.

00:13:11.039 --> 00:13:14.359
So what the really raw data would look like.

00:13:14.359 --> 00:13:18.200
I think that would be perhaps a nice addition

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:23.520
to explain to non-data people what these steps would really

00:13:23.520 --> 00:13:28.039
mean because sometimes I really have the idea that, yeah,

00:13:28.039 --> 00:13:31.359
these non-data people think, oh, the only thing that they do,

00:13:31.359 --> 00:13:33.119
these people is visualize the data,

00:13:33.119 --> 00:13:36.559
but you do so much more than the data visualization

00:13:36.559 --> 00:13:40.679
is usually just the last step in that stacking

00:13:40.679 --> 00:13:43.400
of pre-processing data before you can actually

00:13:43.400 --> 00:13:45.520
make sense of the data.

00:13:45.520 --> 00:13:51.239
Yeah, the transformation of raw data into anything else

00:13:51.239 --> 00:13:54.200
is something I spend a lot of time thinking about.

00:13:54.200 --> 00:13:57.359
In fact, one of my major inspirations for that thinking

00:13:57.359 --> 00:13:58.400
is in this room right now.

00:13:58.400 --> 00:14:07.559
But illustrating that value for different stakeholders

00:14:07.559 --> 00:14:09.080
I think would be really interesting.

00:14:09.080 --> 00:14:13.919
The challenges, as someone else at this conference said,

00:14:13.919 --> 00:14:19.200
all it's an Anna Karenina type of problem

00:14:19.200 --> 00:14:23.280
where all untidy data is different

00:14:23.280 --> 00:14:26.400
and all tidy data is the same.

00:14:26.400 --> 00:14:33.359
And so it's hard to what's nice about doing this reasoning

00:14:33.359 --> 00:14:36.400
about code is that the logic in the code

00:14:36.400 --> 00:14:39.000
gives things like a bounded structure

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:43.679
where sometimes if the raw data is messy enough,

00:14:44.559 --> 00:14:46.200
the structure might be incoherent.

00:14:46.200 --> 00:14:51.119
I mean, I'm sure we've all been down in that dark place before,

00:14:51.119 --> 00:14:52.080
but I appreciate it.

00:14:52.080 --> 00:14:53.799
Thank you.

